Japanese Stock Futures Climb on Growth Outlook; Australian Index Advances

-- B y   A n n a   K i t a n a k a   a n d   T o s h i r o   H a s e g a w a
-- 
2011-03-29T23:23:06Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-29/japanese-stock-futures-climb-on-growth-outlook-australian-index-advances.html
Japanese  stock futures  rose as
companies resumed production following the March 11 earthquake
and tsunami, and on speculation growth abroad will boost
earnings. Australian stocks advanced.  American depositary receipts of Nissan Motor Co. gained 0.3
percent from the closing share price in Tokyo after the carmaker
said it expects its factories in Japan to return to normal by
the end of the first quarter. Those of Toyota Motor Corp., a
carmaker that counts  North America  as its biggest market, rose
0.9 percent. BHP Billiton Ltd., the world’s biggest mining
company, climbed 0.8 percent in Sydney today.  “Even as Japan faces the unexpected effects of the huge
earthquake, the U.S. economic recovery is looking clearer,”
said  Hiroichi Nishi , an equities manager in Tokyo at Nikko
Cordial Securities Inc. “The global economy is recovering.
Starting with Nissan, companies are working hard at restoring
their operations.”  Yen-denominated futures on Japan’s  Nikkei 225 (NKY)  Stock Average
expiring in June closed at 9,500 in Chicago yesterday, compared
with 9,480 in Osaka, Japan. They were bid in the pre-market at
9,460 in Osaka at 8:05 a.m. local time. Australia’s S&P/ASX 200
Index advanced 0.5 percent today. New Zealand’s NZX 50 Index
increased 0.3 percent in Wellington.  Futures on the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index slipped 0.1
percent today. The index rose 0.7 percent to a three-week high
yesterday in  New York  as Home Depot Inc. drove consumer
companies higher and energy shares rose amid speculation
production will increase in the Middle East.  U.S. Economy  U.S. employers added 190,000 jobs in March, according to
economist forecasts before the Labor Department’s April 1
payrolls report. The  unemployment rate  held at 8.9 percent in
March, economists said before the Labor Department reports the
figure. The jobless rate fell below 9 percent in February for
the first time in 22 months.  The MSCI Asia Pacific Index lost 3.4 percent this year to
yesterday, compared with gains of 4.9 percent by the  S&P 500  and
0.3 percent by the Stoxx Europe 600 Index. Stocks in the Asian
benchmark are valued at 13.4 times estimated earnings on
average, compared with 13.6 times for the S&P 500 and 11.1 times
for the Stoxx 600.  The London Metal Exchange Index of prices for six
industrial metals including copper and aluminum gained 0.9
percent yesterday. Crude oil for May delivery increased 0.8
percent to $104.79 a barrel in New York, rising for the first
time in four days.  To contact the reporters on this story:
